{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600647/1930072401/0429.xml":{"full_text":"C-6\nAttractive Slip May Be Made Easily\nBT MARY MARSHALL.\nMost women And It convenient to\nwear thin Summer frocks over separate\nslips Instead of having the dresses made\nwith adequate underslip arrangement as\npart of the dress. It is possible to wash\nand Iron a thin silk or cotton dress in\nthis way, whereas when It is made at\nrra I\nM w\nV V\\\niV I i\nI 0\nill l\nI n\nv i I s I\n*i\nI i\nI\n\ni\ni\ni i\nJ L\nLm I\nBLACK NET EDGES THIS FLESH\nCOLORED SLIP MADE WITH\nPOINTED NECKLINE.\ntached to a slip it must be sent to the\ncleaner.\nToday\u2019s sketch shows a slip that Is as\neasy to make as it is attractive and the\nribbon at the waistline distributes the\nfullness in away that is usually found\nsatisfactory. Slips are rather longer\nthan they used to be and you should\nremember this In getting the material.\nYou should have two lengths, measuring\nfrom two or three inches below the\nshoulder to the edge of the hem, which\nshould be turned up four or five inches.\nThe material should be at least 25\nInches wide. If you have wider material\nyou may use it to make shoulder straps\nand girdle.\nThe slip is so simply constructed that\nyou can draw your pattern from the\nDAILY DIET RECIPE\nNUT AND RAISIN BREAD.\nWhite flour, lYa cups.\nWholewheat flour, 2 cups.\nYellow commeal, Ya cup.\nBrown sugar, cup.\nSalt, 1 teaspoon.\nBaking powder, 4 teaspoons.\nChopped nuts, 1 cup. i\nRaisins. 1 cup. i\nSweet milk, 1 cup.\nMolasses, cup.\nBaking soda, Y* teaspoon.\nMAKES TWO SMALL LOAVES.\nSift first five ingredients to\ngether. Do not discard bran of\nthe whole wheat. .Add nuts and\nraisins. Add milk and mix well.\nCombine soda and molasses and\nadd these to first mixture. Bake\nIn two small greased loaf pans\nIn moderate oven about 45 min\nutes. Dates may be substituted\nfor raisins if desired.\nDIET NOTE.\nRecipe furnishes protein,\nstarch, sugar. Much lime and\niron present but vitamins have\nbeen damaged by action of the\nbaking powder and soda. Can\nbe eaten by normal adults of\naverage or under weight and oc\ncasionally by normal children of\n10 years and over.\nI vilui mm ocrvc wiui w xuppcu wivtuii. 111111150 wj iii\u00abim j niiu h'Jc ni/ uoc> uipu 11511 b \u00a7iccu>\nNO. INDEEOI I HAVEN'T\nITS OLD-FASHIONED. WHY Y U MUST HAVE TOUCHED THAT WASHBOARD\nf ITS OLD-FASHIONED. SCRUBBED THIS SINCE I DISCOVERED\nWHY ARE YOU THROWING I DONT SCRUB MY MORNING-TO OET -!Lm-|WOY*Ai\u00bb MO\nAWAY THAT PERFECTLY CLOTHES ANY MORE THOSE DAZZLING INSO YEARS AGO\nwtM.IIII\nONE WEEK LATER 1 u SaVeS the clothes\u201d M\nLOOK. HENRY... MRS. HART TH E rto^^o^t ,RT\u00df wl O \u25a0if c l? A LttebkeTt\nTOLD ME ABOUT A SOAP L B T SOV\u00bb MT AT V\nCALLED RINSO. IT GOT MY LIKE NEW J OOIQ 12th St. W\nW.H .N0W....* M*\u2014\nfjou. washer. r.comm\u00abd\u00dfm^- a l\nA THE GRANULATED SOAP s laundrie. u.e thw \u00abf\u00ab \u00bb\u00b0\u00bbP I\nveins a\nuse Rinso f \u201ck wa|her and di\u00bbhp an\nWOMAN'S PAGE,\ndiagram with the aid merely of the fol\nlowing dimensions:\nFront.\nAB\u2014Desired length of the slip.\nBD\u2014Twelve inches.\nAC\u2014Five Inches.\nCE \u2014Nine and one-half inches.\nAF \u2014Four and three-fourth Inches.\nBack.\nAB\u2014One-half inch shorter than front\nAB.\nAC\u2014Four and one-half inches.\nBD\u2014Twelve inches.\nCE\u2014Nine and one-half inches.\nAF\u2014Four and three-fourth inches.\nThe figures given here are for a\nmedium-sized slip and do not include\nallowances for seams and narrow hems.\nSUB ROSA\nBT MIMI.\nFlorette is hard to satisfy. She even\nfinds it most difficult to please herself.\nYou know her\u2014there are many like\nher. She is a universal type.\nShe is the fussy girl.\nThe story of the princess who dis\ncovered the pea under 20 mattresses\ncould well be applied to Florette \u2014she\nis as particular as that. She spends\na great deal of time making her bed\nso there is not a wrinkle in it. Other\nwise. she says, she wouldn\u2019t get a wink\nof sleep.\nWhen she puts on a hat, it must be\nJust so. If it isn\u2019t, she is miserable.\nWhen she combs her hair, each hair\nmust be Just so, the wave over her\ntemple must fall in the exact manner\nshe wishes it to. Otherwise she is\nwretched. When she applies the pow\nder puff to her nose she spends a\ngreat deal more time than is neces\nsary to accomplish the result she de\nsires.\nIt takes Florette a long time to make\nup her mind about her hats and\nclothes. First she has to decide on\nthe style and then on the color. Then,\nhaving decided on one thing, she\nchanges her mind over and over again.\nShe never tires of looking at herself\nin the mirror. She looks at herself\nfrom every angle\u2014and then does it all\nover again, not quite satisfied with the\nresults.\nShe Is a great trial to dressmakers\nand shop clerks. They know when\nthey see her coming that they are in\nfor a difficult siege of trying to please\nher.\nAnd time means absolutely nothing\nto her. She is frequently late for ap\npointments\u2014something always detains\nher. It may be that she puts on one\npair of stockings, and after surveying\nher entire get-up. feels that she must\nchange to another color.\nWhen she goes in bathing she is sure\nto be the last one of her crowd to get\ninto the water. She has to see that her\nbathing outfit exactly meets her ap\nproval\u2014and that each garment she has\ntaken off is just so, before she leaves\nthe bath house.\nThen she walks out into the water,\nshivers a long while and fisses around\ntrying to make up her inind to duck\nherself.\nIt is amazing that one so young\nshould be as fussy as Tlorette. She\neven fusses about the young men she\ngoes with. When she is invited out by\none she doesn\u2019t know whether she\nought to accept the invitation or not\u2014\nand when she finally does accept she\nhas a difficult time making up her\nmind where she should go.\nShe is a fussy girl.\nMaybe the author can help you with\nyour problems. Write her, sending\nstamped, self-addressed envelope for\npersonal reply.\nFillet* of Fish.\nUse any fresh fish from which strips\nwithout skin and bone may be taken.\nScrape a little onion Juice over the fish\nand season with salt, then roll in soft,\nsifted bread crumbs. Beat an egg and\nadd three tablespoonfuis of milk or\nwater. Pour the egg over the pieces of\nfish to baste each piece completely,\nthen again roll in crumbs, and fry in\nhot fat to a golden brown. Serve hot\nwith a cupful of mayonnaise dressing\nto which two tablespoonfuls each of\nchopped capers, olives, pickles and pars\nley have been added. The fat is at the\nright temperature when it will brown a\ncrumb of bread in a minute.\nCold Fruit Dessert*.\n1. Arrange crushed pineapples or\nsliced poaches in alternate layers with\ncocoanut and whipped cream.\n2. Put sliced peaches or crushed\npineapple in glasses and cover with\nboiled custard. Just before serving pile\negg whites, beaten stiff and mixed with\npowdered sugar, on top of each glass.\n3. Add cooked apricots, sliced peaches\nor crushed pineapple to lemon or orange\nJelly just before it becomes firm. Mold,\nchill and serve with whiDDed cream.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON. D. C.. THURSDAY. JULY 24. 1930.\nToday in\nWashington History\nBT DONALD A. CKAIO.\nJuly 24, 1861. \u2014Since the Battle of\nBull Run, three days ago, military men\nand others have been indulging in con\ntroversies over \"who stopped the retreat\nof the Union troops?\u201d The Evening\nStar today declares that \"whatever may\nbe said to the contrary,\u201d these are the\nfacts:\nA company of reinforcements for\nHunt\u2019s Battery of the Union Army,\ncommanded by Lieut. Brlsbln, was the\nfirst to halt. These men were unarmed,\nbut they threw themselves across the\nroad, and, taking arms from those who\ncame up. prevented Union fugitives\nfrom passing to the rear.\n\"Their position,\u201d says The Evening\nStar, \"was on the hill about one-half\nmile on the road leading from Center\nville to Fairfax. They held their posi\ntion for nearly two hours, when a re\nport that the Secession Cavalry was\nadvancing down a ravin* half a mile to\nthe rear to cut off this retreat, Induced\nLieut. Brisbin to fall back beyond the\nravine, where he again took up a posi\ntion across the road, resting the right\nwing on a thick wood and the left\nagainst a high hill, thus cutting off all\nretreat.\u201d\nThis second position was held, The\nStar goes on to say, for two hours\nlonger, or until Col. Montgomery came\nup with reinforcements of several New\nJersey regiments. Lieut. Brisbin had\nthree men shot while trying to stop the\nheadlong retreat. He himself was\nwounded in the battle with the Confed\nerates, and again while endeavoring to\nstop the fugitives from the Union Army.\nThe War Department today an\nnounced that there now are actually on\nthe railroads, headed for Washington,\n16 full regiments of \u201cthree-year,\u201d or\n\"for-the-war\u201d men, who are expected\nto reach here at any time during the\nnext 24 hours, to strengthen the Union\nArmy. Six of these regiments arrived in\nBaltimore yesterday and are due by rail\nroad any minute.\nEleven more Union regiments from\nthe Northern and Western States are\ndue to move to Washington at once, to\nadd to the strength of the defenses here\nor to take the field against the Confed\nerates, if that course should b* deemed\nadvisable.\nPERSONAL HEALTH SERVICE\nBY WILLIAM BRADY, M. D.\nI\nThe Tonsil Situation.\nIn England McKenzie has gone on\nrecord as saying that he Is convinced\n(I quote from an abstract published In\nthe Journal of the American Medical\nAssociation) that diathermy extirpation\nof the tonsils will come to be the\nmethod of choice for adults. McKenzie\nconsiders it not suitable for children,\nthough in this country some of the\nmore skilled throat specialists employ\nit with satisfaction for some children\nonly four or five years old. The only\nreason why it is not so suitable for\nchildren is that it is much more dif\nficult to secure the necessary co-opera\ntion from a young child. So It depends\nlargely upon the personal factor\u2014both\nthe kind of training the child has had\nJOLLY POLLY\nA Lesson in English.\nBI JOSEPH J. FRISCH.\nTHIS HEADING APPEARED IN\nOUR NEWSPAPER FAMOUS\nINVENTOR WILL ENDEAVOR TO\nELIMINATE NOISE IN INDUSTRY.*'\nWHEN DAD READ THESE\nTIDINGS. HE SAID, 'AFTER THAT.\nHE MIGHT TACKLE A*\n\nN. A. R.\u2014\u201c When Dad read this news,\u201d\nis the required form. \u201cNews\u201d is gen\neral; \"tidings\u201d are personal. We read\nthe news daily; we wait for tidings re\nspecting an absent friend. We receive\nnews of the battle and tidings of friends\nengaged in it.\nThe present tendency Is to restrict\n\"tldines\u201d to literary and poetic use.\ncf c Jkc\nPAWS f \\Wyii\n\u00b0Jhe sheen of blue.- /At Ji\nn satin and long I\nare the beauty\\\nof\ndinner frock with,\nqodets in the bolero. 1 j\nI\nand the patience or knack of the doctor\nfor managing children.\nIn England, however, they seem to\nthink the new-fangled method ie not so\nbad. I have no first-hand knowledge of\nEnglish medical and surgical practice,\nbut from literature I gather that they\u2019re\nnot quite so radical about surgery over\nthere.\nOver here, to read some of these\nmedical journal screeds, one might\nImagine that it Is lese majesty or trea\nson for a physician of unassailable pro\nfessional standing\u2014that Is, membership\nor fellowship In his local, State and na\ntional medical societies\u2014to Imply that\nnormal tonsils should not be removed,\nor to deplore the risks and the serious\ncomplications of surgical tonsillectomy\nand suggest some safer and equally ef\nfective remedy.\nAll these editorial doctors are excel\nlent in their Held. Some of them, how\never, have never had any experience to\nspeak of In the practice of medicine.\nI had had 15 years of It before I began\nto tell the world. Therefore, I consider\nmyself a competent judge of the ton\nsillectomy question and of diathermy\nextirpation.\n(Signed letters pertaining to personal\nhealth and hygiene, not to disease,\ndiagnosis or treatment, will be answered\noy Dr. Brady if a stamped, self-ad\ndressed envelope is inclosed. Letters\nshould be brief and written in ink.\nOwing to the large number of letters re\nceived only a few can be answered here.\nNo reply can be made to queries not\nconforming to instructions. Address Dr.\nWilliam Braoy in care of The Evening\nStar.)\n(Copyright, 1M0.)\nEggs in Aspio.\nCut six hard-boiled eggs In halves\nlengthwise, remove the yolks, and mash\nthree. Add to the mashed yolks three\ntablespoonfuls of melted butter, three\nancholvles finely chopper, two teaspoon\nfuls of tarragon vinegar, one table\nspoonfu lof Trench mustard, half a\ntablespoonful of chopped capers, half\na teaspoonful of paprika and one\nteaspoonful of salt When well blended\nfill the halves of the egg whites with the\nmixture and coat with aspic. Arrange\nslices of chilled tomatoes on a serving\ndish, marinate with French dressing,\nand place on each a prepared egg and\nsurround with chopped aspic Jelly col\nored llarht rreen.\nThare\u2019a the kick of HEALTH In\nthis pure juice of luscious Concord\nCrapes. A glass before retiring\nmakes you sleep like a top\nupon arising, clears your brain\nand puts an edge on appetite.\nTry It, toe, for broakCut. Mi liberal\nportion* to the pint... more if diluted,\nand many prefer It eo. Leea than 5c a\nportion I The moat temptingly deli\neloua breakfeat fruit Julca In America.\nInalat on Welch's. h'i Pasteurised.\nPer free health booltln, write\nWelch's, Peps. D, Wtttfitld, N. Y.\nw m\nJ| Never Accept The \u201cJust As Good\u201d v\nI Because You Want Quality DEMAND I\nI Schneiders 1\nRye Bread\nI Schneider y s B\nI Vienna Bread I\nI You See The Difference I\nI You Taste The Difference I\nfi Superior Quality Has Made Both Washington's Unchallenged I\nFavor